segments.text: We know that a lot of students, or some students anyway, had part-time jobs, and I believe you mentioned earlier at one point that you, I believe, worked in the library.
C.C.
Yeats was a senior my first year, and he asked me if I wanted to work in the chem lab with him, and I took the job for 15 or 20 cents an hour.
I don't know what it was.
And the next year,
I'd been in the library so much, I got to voluntarily helping doing things, straightening up things.
And so the lady in charge asked me if I wanted the job, and I took it for 20 cents an hour.
And I kept those jobs through my senior year, not in chemistry, only my junior, senior year.
But the last year in college, I still worked in the, didn't work in either one of them, actually.
the last year I was there, when I went back in January 1919.
But I made my expenses at $0.20 an hour on average working in either chemistry or in the library during that period.
I got some help from home.
All I asked for, I wouldn't ask for it because I wanted to do it on my own.
since I'd been out of school four years before I went to A&M.
My money was lost in a bank failure in Fort Worth three months before school opened, and I was broke after saving for four years.
That must have been quite a blow.
Yep.
Did the athletes on campus when you were there receive any particularly special treatment?
Only into the
that they had a separate table, I think, in the dormitory.
But as for special favors to athletes, I don't think there were any.
Basically, they had to make the drill and abide by the rules that the rest of you did.
They had to abide.
Well, some rules they drilled and things of that kind.
Some of it they got out of.
Didn't have to do it.
But I don't think there was any special effort to get out of anything.
Were a goodly percentage of them on scholarship?
I don't think there was any scholarships at that time.
In my impression, there wasn't.
I think they were all there on their own.
They just were there for the fun of it.
Yeah, they just, there were no scholarships.
I never heard of a scholarship while I was at A&M College.
Okay.
In looking through your senior yearbook, I noticed that you were a member of the, I guess it's K-E-B-L-E, Keeble Club.
The Keeble Club was an organization.
I don't know who started it.
It was in existence before I got there.
It was started by a group of Episcopal students.
Keeble was one of the outstanding Roman Catholic, I guess you'd call him a missionary.
I can't give you his history.
I've forgotten.
I hadn't heard of that in so long.
But the opposite was for the Catholic boys.
And theirs is the, oh, my memory's terrible.
The Catholic boys had their own, and the name they selected was the great scholastic minister who was an Episcopalian.
It went over to Catholic.
Keeble was Catholic, went over to Episcopalian.
Now, that's a rough history of that back there.
But we met once a month in a dormitory room.
But the local minister from downtown would come out and visit with us.
And we'd talk generalities.
There wasn't any religious activities connected with it.
And that's the only thing I remember about that.
Of course, we had a Fort Worth club.
It met once or two or three times a year.
So we'd recognize each other.
At that time, I knew everybody from Fort Worth.
But they've all disappeared.
And let's see, you were also in the SAA.
That was what?
FAA?
SAA.
Student Agricultural Association or something?
It was something like that, but I don't remember any activities connected with it.
What about the horticultural society?
We had a horticultural society, which only met once or twice.
I've forgotten what we did, actually.
I don't remember even the members of it.
I'd have to look in the .
I assume it was primarily horticulture.
Yeah.
Earlier, you sort of summarized your career from graduation.
work in China, and at one point while we had the mic off, you were telling me something about the one factor which influenced your decision to go to China, about the lecturer who was on campus.
Yes, Frank N. Myers, who gave his lecture on his experiences in China, and I experienced many of the same things on my own, because I've walked across China twice myself, and
but not in the area that he had been, that he reflected to me, because he was in northwest China where an ox cart was possible.
I have never lived in China where an ox cart was possible.
I've had either sedan chairs or rowboats or walking, and I've walked across most of China, central China.
Living in China, of course, is much like living in a country as large as the United States.
A person who has lived in New York all his life doesn't know anything about the Big Bend industry.
He wouldn't know how people lived in South Texas.
And people live in Shanghai all their life, or all the time in China, have no conception whatsoever of the rest of the countries.
And that goes people in the north or south, so you get many conflicting impressions of the country.
After you came back from China then and things erupted in China and you were in the United States, presumably you were then without a job back in China.
Yes, I came back to the United States and was here for a year.
My company finally decided they couldn't send me back.
But in case I would go back, they asked me if there was anything I wanted to do.
And I told them I wanted to take a training course in motor rebuilding at the Ford Motor Company.
And they arranged that.
I went out to Ford Motor Company in Detroit and spent two months rebuilding automobile engines so that I could get the equipment to establish in China to service the motors we had already sold.
And I also had about 80% of all the tire sales in China, central China, because I knew the name and make and owner of every car in there, because it was a limited area where you could drive a car.
And outside of the foreign community, you couldn't.
And so I went to Goodyear for, I don't know, six months, I guess.
I learned how to build tires and rebuild them and repair them.
They put me on the export desk for Central America and I stayed there for the rest of that part of that year.
picked a man who had never been out of the United States to send him to China to take the place of my favorite district manager in the company in China.
And so I quit there.
And I then took a job with
an oil company, HH Oil Company, in West Texas in Big Spring.
And I worked as a roughneck for six months until I nearly got killed and I quit.
And I went back to the company in New York, and we finally decided I wasn't going back to China.
And I met an executive of this associated oil company who had a refinery in Patterson, New Jersey.
So with my experience in that, I went down there and they put me through a course of combining fuel oils, lubricating oils, and I stayed there for a few weeks.
I accidentally walked into the Texaco office, Foreign Department, and told them who it was.
And I wanted to find out where J.C. Williams was, the person I knew in China who lived with me.
And he told me.
And in the course of it, he asked me if I wanted to go back to China.
And I told him I did someday.
And I gave him my name and address.
I was staying at the Times Square Hotel.
The next morning at eight o'clock, he called me up and asked me if I'd come down to the office.
He wanted to talk to me.
And he laid before me this request from the Shanghai District Office that they'd like to have me back out there.
And this was two weeks before Christmas.
We talked it over.
He said, well, while your thing is over, would you mind finding out something about our products?
Well, I said, I know about your products.
Your man lived with me for four years.
And I've been using it on motor cars in China.
And I said, it's almost as good as standard oil products.
And he left.
So he sent me over to Long Island City for weeks training on their oils.
And, of course, my experience as a roughneck in the oil field and also with Union Associated Oil, they thought it would be a good idea if I took this job to go out to China.
So I told him I would like to go in January.
Well, he said, we have a boat leaving the 6th of January from Seattle.
And I said, well, I have to get back to Texas and get things straightened up because then there's a week before Christmas.
before I, January 6th would be too early.
And he immediately said that, well, if I was working for a hard-boiled outfit, and that they wasn't accustomed to giving two weeks vacation to somebody before they hired them.
And he said, I see there's a boat on the 21st of January, and if you don't own the whole damn state of Texas, you ought to be able to get ready at that time.
So I came back home and packed and went back to China with the Texas Company.
And of course I knew the territory and I knew the Chinese and knew the companies and knew all the hooks and crooks of dealing with the Chinese.
Everything was fine until my district manager made a big blunder.
ship load of kerosene up through the Yangtze Gorges at the time when the price was highest.
The rate's always higher in wintertime when the water's low.
And I was opposed to it, but he shipped it anyhow because he had a friend in the English community who he was toady into because he was so excellent at the country club.
And they shipped it up there, and it lay out in the harbor for 10 days in the rain on a flat boat.
And we paid the taxes on it, the internal taxes.
And when the general in charge of the area came down, we couldn't produce tax sheets.
The Englishmen in charge of shipping it on an English boat up through the gorges couldn't be found, and they taxed us again on it.
And we losthad all these cases exposed to rain, and they began to rust and to leak.
And we got it up to Chongqing a week or two later.

They had 800 gallons lost, and the Chinese came and dipped it up with tin cans and what have you out of the ship and located it on the foreshore where they had not any place to store it except in a Chinese hut.
and there was kerosene leaking all over the place, one that didn't all catch fire.

Well, they sent me up there to straighten that out, and they also sent up an interpreter who was a professional detective who had worked for Standard Oil for many years, and he had the record of this, and he double-crossed me because I couldn't speak the Sichuanese language, and he took a fifth of one-tenth or one-tenth of a percent off of
Comshaw for each case, and we finally found a place outside of the city limits of what we'd call the harbor limits there.
A Chinese house was roofed in with bamboo, and you could put 30,000 cases in there, and we did, and then they had to hire men to look after it.
And the reason I took it, because it was the only place available, and it was right in the middle of the thieves' union territory.
You have unions of thieves in China, and you have to play with the thieves, not the police.
Because when the thieves steal anything, they know who got it.
And if they don't, somebody gets the throat cut.
When it was found out, of course, and reported to New York, and they got wind of it, I put their cargo in the center of a thieves outfit.
And I was paying the thieves $50 a month just to look after it.
And the thieves, of course, were not going to let anybody else steal it.
And they were satisfied.
They'd get more money that way than they was getting any other way, illegitimately.
And this was perfectly safe.
The company sent another detective up there, their own up there, and they found this fellow chiseling for $7,000.
And so we had a big racket, and the interpreter disappeared, and I never have known what happened to him.
I took him as interpreter to see one of the Tuchans across the river, and it turned out that
This Tuchin had a reward out for his head, because he had stole one of these concubines.
And we went in, and he interpreted our discourses and made an agreement as to the treatment of our men down on the waterfront.
And I didn't find this out till after he came back.
And he disappeared.
The general in charge of ,, his men picked him up and beheaded him.
I assume they did.
I never found out what happened.
So I came back downriver and had a long story of horror to tell them.
And so they said, well, you better get back down to Shanghai district.
And when I went to Shanghai, the first thing that told me he wanted me to go to Korea.
And I went to Korea for six or eight months.
I came back to Shanghai, and that time the Depression hit.
was still reflecting on us out there.
They came back, and eight or 10 of the people who had been with them for 25 years were cashiered because they couldn't keep them any longer, and all of their hard plans had been messed up.
And so they said that they'd have to cancel my contract.
And so that was satisfying to me because things were getting pretty rough.
though I took my money and got on a boat and went around the world, stayed a few weeks, months in India and Egypt and France and Germany and England.
And when I landed back in New York with red lines a mile long, a very depressing time, I got all my junk back to Texas.
and then went back to the University of Pennsylvania and just got on a streetcar and drove out there and enrolled.
And I stayed there until 1937 when I accidentally came down here and contacted these people at Tech.
Two years later, I came down here.
Did you teach at University of Pennsylvania then?
No, I was a graduate student there.
I took the business administration course, then I took the doctoral course.
And I was writing my thesis between 36 and 39.
And when the war started, the Japanese oriental division of the Library of Congress double-crossed me out of all of my documented references.
And so I knew I couldn't finish it.
So then I gave up.
Meantime, I got married.
And so we landed in here in 1940.
I did Texas Tech.
And I stayed there until I retired in 62.
OK.
So that's how come you were, the business course you took was what made you teach economics and management rather than horticulture, which was your undergraduate major.
Yes.
See, I'd been so far away from agriculture for those years because I'd been in shipping and international trade.
International relations.
So I majored in international economics at the university.
And then did you ever finish your doctorate?
No.
No.
My first son was my doctorate.
I didn't expect him so soon.
And arriving down here, then the war destroyed all of the pertinence of my four years accumulation of information.
I had to run for three years at the Department of Commerce, Department of State.
I was in both those.
I knew everybody in there in those days.
It was very simple.
Of course, you couldn't get in there without an armed guard now, but I knew everybody in there in those days.
And so then you were at Texas Tech in the economics department from, what, 40?
And of course, in 42, they made me head of department.
And I stayed head of department until I retired from that in 65.
And of course, remained there the next three years.
Made it 22 years in all when I retired in 62.
What have you been doing since you retired?
Well, unfortunately, my wife developed Parkinson's disease, and that limited our activities.
We visited with relatives in various places in Texas.
I mean, Fort Worth primarily.
But as she grew worse, she required more of my attention.
And I became her sole nurse for the next 10 years.
And she died June a year ago.
And I've spent all my time the last four years as a nurse around the clock.
And I've only been out of town once in four years.
Week before last, I went up to Wisconsin to visit my son, who's with General Motors up there, and I had a week with him.
It's the only time I've had one night out of my house in nearly five years.
Okay.
Albert Atkinson was a CE student enlisted in this 32nd Service Company with me, and he was what we call a photographer buff today.
And when these airplanes, one of them landed there, I think it was out of Houston or someplace down there.
This was on campus?
On campus.
He had talked this fellow into taking him up and let him take pictures.
And he took pictures of the campus.
And I have three or four of them he gave me.
And I would suggest that if you could see him in Dallas, and he's in the student directory there.
Albert Atkinson, 29.
I think he must have had a son or two because there's two more Atkinsons down there.
But he's CE 1920.
Actually, I think he was, well, I think that was it.
No, he was class of 19, I think.
But I'd just love to see him.
I haven't seen him since I left college.
He was the same man who took the picture of the University of Texas steer that was branded.
I think that's right, and I have a picture of that, too.
That occurred while you were a student, did it not?
Yes, that was one of the big episodes.
We've had a good bit of interest in that just recently, my assistant and I have.
As a matter of fact, he went down to McAllen and interviewed Hans Rohde, who did the branding.
Hans Rohde did the branding.
Got a good story from him about the branding.
I like to read that sometimes, it's a memory.

Rodie also sent us in the mail an invitation to a barbecue that he thought occurred in 22 but I believe it was actually 1920 and this would have been during your senior year that apparently with this 13 to nothing brand on the side of the animal some people have said they the University of Texas over branded it to read Bevo
and we can't find any proof of that.
Some people have said the animal never made another public appearance.
It never made another public appearance as far as I know.
You see, I left the country after that, but from the impression I got when I got back there, I got back and talked to some people.
I understood that they disposed of that animal.
Well, Rhodey sent us an invitation to a banquet in Austin in 1920.

which supposedly they had killed this animal and had a barbecue over in austin and they invited people from a m and people from university of texas to it and supposedly uh according to a newspaper clipping we have they split to hide one school got one half and the other school got the other half i don't know who got the branded half we've never been able to track that down oh that was big days and exciting that's one of the most exciting things that ever happened i've been looking back on it
That was really something.
The school went wild.
Well, there was another one afterwards.
Or was it before?
We went down to Houston and beat the Owls.
And I think it was the first time we'd beat them in years.
And they had a mascot.
It was a big stuffed owl.
And a group of students swiped it and ran down the street with it and put it on the train and expressed it at a college station.
And the Rice student body tried to come down and recover it, and the express company wouldn't release it, of course.
And they brought that back.
And we had an armory up on the third floor of the administration in the northeast corner, and they stored it in there.
And some Rice students came up there, and they stayed on the campus as visitors for three or four days.
And they finally found out where that was, where it was hidden.
So one night, they went up there with crowbars and broke that open and got the thing down those three flights, staring into a car.
And it had no better sense than to parade around the campus yelling, we got the owl.
And so they started off those dirt roads all the way down to Houston then, you see.
And so it happened just 3 o'clock in the morning.
The whole student body, nice shirts and everything else.
They got on a train to beat it down to Navasota to head it off.
And some went in cars that they could scramble to get the very many cars around.
But they finally got a bridge over a creek down there.
They got there before this car and the Bryce group went off in the woods and burned it up rather than have it captured.
That was pretty exciting.
But they brought those people back, kept them on the campus as prisoners for three or four days.
It was all good natured stuff, but it was lots of excitement.
Yeah, that was a pretty good story.
That sort of stuff really can't go on anymore, I don't think.
They've pilfered a few things over the last two years, but not anything like that.
Oh, a couple years ago, they stole the university steer again.
They did.
Brought it over to campus and braided it around for a while, and then they took it back, or
allowed it to go back.
There's something happened to the spirit of students out at Tech, even in the faculty.
For the years I was there, our faculty was closely associated, especially in the Division of Business Administration.
We were all closely associated.
Of course, we were on two floors.
And we had meetings with each other all the time.
And we'd have social meetings, three formal ones through the year.
And the students seemed to be closer together.
And there wasn't any friction.
But now I'm told I haven't been on the campus much since I retired because I
As they say, I had to stay at home.
And when the cars got so numerous that it was difficult to park, and after I hurt my feet, I couldn't.
It was too uncomfortable to walk up there.
And then they finally put the administration over in the new high rise building.
And they're all on different floors.
And they don't see each other once a year.
And they don't even know the names of the new people that know the people who come in.
Across the campus, there's so many new people come in.
The faculty's tripled in numbers.
And people don't know each other except in their own division.
And when I said to someone here recently, who is this new man you got in economics?
He said, I haven't met him.
I don't know.
So you have that spirit.
They don't have parties anymore, social activities.
I think this is true at many, many schools.
We used to have a little place down there where the agriculture building is.
Now there's a little tree, some forest there, a few trees.
And we'd have faculty picnics down there.
And then we used the old, what do you call it, the auditorium or the place where the judge am.
We used to have parties in there two or three times a year, the whole faculty.
And of course, you could get the whole faculty in one room then.
There was room 225 that would hold 100.
We'd get everybody in there.
Today, they haven't got a building.
They're big enough to take care of things, let alone the students.
